  "prompt": "How do calculate the gear ratio?",
  "response": "Calculating gear ratio involves comparing the number of teeth on two gears that are meshed together. The basic formula for gear ratio is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driven Gear}}{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driving Gear}} \\]\n\nWhere:\n- The driving gear (also called the input gear or driver) is the gear connected to the power source.\n- The driven gear (also called the output gear) is the gear being turned by the driving gear.\n\nHere\u2019s a step-by-step process to calculate the gear ratio:\n\n1. **Identify the Number of Teeth**: Count the number of teeth on both the driving gear and the driven gear.\n\n2. **Apply the Formula**: Use the formula given above to find the gear ratio.\n\nFor example, if the driving gear has 20 teeth and the driven gear has 40 teeth, the gear ratio is:\n\n\\[ \\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{40}{20} = 2:1 \\]\n\nThis means the driven gear turns at half the speed of the driving gear, but with twice the torque.\n\nFor more complex gear systems (like compound gear trains), you may need to multiply the gear ratios of each pair of gears involved.\n\n\\[ \\text{Compound Gear Ratio} = \\text{Ratio of Gear Pair 1} \\times \\text{Ratio of Gear Pair 2} \\times \\ldots \\]\n\nExample: If you have a system with two gear pairs, with the first pair having a ratio of 3:1 and the second pair having a ratio of 4:1, the overall gear ratio would be:\n\n\\[ \\text{Compound Gear Ratio} = 3 \\times 4 = 12:1 \\]\n\nThis would mean the final output gear turns much slower and has more torque compared to the initial driving gear.",
